1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,530
Chapter 13 How to Think Like a Leader Remind yourself once again that you are not pulled to high levels of success.

2
00:00:10,800 --> 00:00:15,970
Rather, you are lifted there by those working beside and below you.

3
00:00:17,200 --> 00:00:27,970
Achieving high-level success requires the support and the cooperation of others, and gaining this support and cooperation of others requires leadership ability.

4
00:00:28,321 --> 00:00:35,730
Success and the ability to lead others, that is, getting them to do things they wouldn't do if they were not led,

5
00:00:35,841 --> 00:00:37,251
go hand in hand.

6
00:00:38,081 --> 00:00:47,091
The success-producing principles explained in the previous chapters are valuable equipment in helping you develop your leadership capacity.

7
00:00:47,441 --> 00:00:56,851
At this point, we want to master four special leadership rules or principles that can cause others to do things for us in the executive suite,

8
00:00:56,881 --> 00:01:02,211
in business, in social clubs, in the home, anywhere we find people.

9
00:01:03,201 --> 00:01:08,291
These four leadership rules or principles are 1.

10
00:01:08,720 --> 00:01:11,970
Trade minds with the people you want to influence.

11
00:01:11,970 --> 00:01:12,770
2.

12
00:01:13,121 --> 00:01:13,811
Think.

13
00:01:14,080 --> 00:01:16,690
What is the human way to handle this?

14
00:01:17,440 --> 00:01:22,531
Three, think progress, believe in progress, push for progress.

15
00:01:22,961 --> 00:01:29,330
Four, take time out to confer with yourself and develop your supreme thinking power.

16
00:01:30,481 --> 00:01:33,410
Practicing these rules produces results.

17
00:01:33,521 --> 00:01:40,611
Putting them to use in everyday situations takes the mystery out of that gold-plated word, leadership.

18
00:01:40,961 --> 00:01:42,291
Let's see how.

19
00:01:44,241 --> 00:01:49,970
Leadership rule number one, trade minds with the people you want to influence.

20
00:01:50,961 --> 00:01:56,130
Trading minds with the people you want to influence is a magic way to get others,

21
00:01:56,321 --> 00:02:02,531
friends, associates, customers, employees, to act the way you want them to act.

22
00:02:02,961 --> 00:02:06,691
Study these two case histories and see why.

23
00:02:07,600 --> 00:02:13,810
Ted B. worked as a television copywriter and director for a large advertising agency.

24
00:02:14,160 --> 00:02:23,891
When the agency obtained a new account, a children's shoe manufacturer, Ted was assigned responsibility for developing several TV commercials.

25
00:02:24,560 --> 00:02:35,330
A month or so after the campaign had been launched, it became clear that the advertising was doing little or nothing to increase product movement in retail outlets.

26
00:02:35,680 --> 00:02:43,011
Attention was focused on the TV commercials, because in most cities only television advertising was used.

27
00:02:43,840 --> 00:02:51,490
Through research of television viewers, they found that about 4% of the people thought it was simply a great commercial.

28
00:02:51,520 --> 00:02:54,370
One of the best, these 4% said.

29
00:02:54,960 --> 00:03:02,451
The remaining 96% were either indifferent to the commercials or, in plain language, thought they smelled.

30
00:03:02,960 --> 00:03:06,050
Hundreds of comments like these were volunteered.

31
00:03:06,320 --> 00:03:07,251
It's wacky.

32
00:03:07,280 --> 00:03:14,210
The rhythm sounds like a New Orleans band at 3 a.m. My kids like to watch most TV commercials,

33
00:03:14,240 --> 00:03:18,851
but when that shoe thing comes on, they go to the bathroom or refrigerator.

34
00:03:19,761 --> 00:03:22,291
I think it's too uppity-up.

35
00:03:22,400 --> 00:03:25,650
Seems to me someone's trying to be too clever.

36
00:03:26,641 --> 00:03:32,770
Something especially interesting turned up when all the interviews were put together and analyzed.

37
00:03:33,120 --> 00:03:42,050
The 4% who liked the commercial were people pretty much like Ted in terms of income, education, sophistication, and interests.

38
00:03:42,320 --> 00:03:48,131
The remaining 96% were definitely in a different socioeconomic class.

39
00:03:48,720 --> 00:03:55,091
Ted's commercials, which cost a lot of money, flopped because Ted thought only of his own interests.

40
00:03:55,440 --> 00:04:02,210
He had prepared the commercials thinking of the way he buys shoes, not the way the great majority buys shoes.

41
00:04:02,560 --> 00:04:09,891
He developed commercials that pleased him personally, not commercials that pleased the great bulk of the people.

42
00:04:10,800 --> 00:04:19,810
The results would have been much different had Ted projected himself into the minds of the masses of ordinary people and asked himself two questions.

43
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:25,250
If I were a parent, what kind of a commercial would make me want to buy those shoes?

44
00:04:25,520 --> 00:04:32,370
If I were a child, what kind of a commercial would make me go tell my mom or dad that I want those shoes?

